{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nStamp denormalized author identity on every mutating event (git-style: a name and\nan email travel *in* the event), plus an OPTIONAL `author_id` referencing an\n`identity` ticket (from ddbe) — all at rebar's single locked write seam\n(`_seam.py::append_event`), without breaking replay of events written before this\nchange. This is the attribution substrate the authorship attestation (bde5) and\nenforcement (3183) build on.\n\n## Why\nAuthorship certification needs every event to record who wrote it in a form that\nsurvives replication and compaction (denormalized, not a lookup). An optional\n`author_id` links to the rich `identity` entity when one is resolvable, while the\ndenormalized name/email keep working when it is not (identity is opt-in).\n\n## What\n### 1. Stamp attribution at the single write seam (`src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py`)\n`append_event` already builds the envelope `{timestamp, uuid, event_type, env_id,\nauthor, data}` and stamps `author` (name) via the existing `author()` helper\n(`git config user.name`). Extend the envelope there — the ONE seam every write\n(create/edit/transition/link/comment/tag/sign/...) flows through:\n- Add an `author_email()` helper mirroring `author()`: returns `git config\n  user.email` (stripped), or `\"\"` when unset / the git call fails (never raises).\n- Add `\"author_email\": author_email()` to the envelope UNCONDITIONALLY.\n- Add `\"author_id\": <id>` to the envelope ONLY when a current identity resolves\n  (`rebar._commands.identity.resolve_current_identity(repo_root=...)` is not None);\n  OMIT the key entirely when None (keeps the envelope minimal + back-compatible).\n- The batch-sink path (deferred commit) composes through the SAME envelope block,\n  so buffered events are byte-identical — do not add the fields downstream of the\n  sink branch.\n\n### 2. Performance: resolve at most once per process\n`append_event` is the hot write path and `resolve_current_identity` scans identity\ntickets + shells git. Memoize `author_email` and `author_id` per `repo_root` for\nthe process lifetime (module-level cache, e.g. a dict keyed by resolved repo root,\nor `functools.lru_cache` on small helpers) so a batch of N writes does NOT do N\ngit calls + N ticket scans. A single session's identity does not change mid-run;\nthe cache is process-scoped (never persisted).\n\n### 3. Replay back-compat (reducer surfaces attribution PRESENT-ONLY)\n`src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py` already reads `event.get(\"author\")` (None-safe).\nSurface the new fields **present-only** (mirrors the identity payload + `source_*`\nhandling): set `state[\"author_email\"]` / `state[\"author_id\"]` ONLY when the event\ncarries them. Consequences:\n- An event written BEFORE this change (no `author_email`/`author_id`) reduces to\n  **byte-identical** compiled state — no new keys appear, so \"same state\" holds\n  exactly, and nothing can crash on a missing key.\n- A new event surfaces `author_email` always and `author_id` when an identity was\n  resolved, so bde5 can read `author_id` off compiled state.\nApply the present-only surfacing at each CREATE/edit/transition processor that\nalready stamps `author` (the 3-4 sites at `_processors.py`).\n\n## Scope\nIn: the `author_email()` helper, the envelope stamping + per-process cache, the\nreducer present-only surfacing, and the back-compat regression test. Out:\nsigning/verifying authorship (bde5), key lifecycle (e165), enforcement (3183).\n`author_id` is populated but NOT yet verified or required here.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Every mutating event's envelope carries a denormalized author `name`\n  (existing `author`) AND `author_email`; a test writes an event and asserts the\n  raw stored event JSON contains both. When a current identity is resolved\n  (`rebar identity use <id>`), the same write also carries `author_id == <id>`;\n  when none resolves, the `author_id` key is ABSENT (test both branches).\n- [ ] Regression/back-compat: a hand-authored event stream WITHOUT\n  `author_email`/`author_id` reduces without error to the SAME compiled state\n  (no `author_email`/`author_id` keys surfaced) as before the change — asserted by\n  a test that reduces a synthetic pre-change event and diffs the state dict.\n- [ ] The stamping happens at the single `_seam.py::append_event` seam (verified\n  observably: writing via two DIFFERENT commands — e.g. `create` and `comment` —\n  both yield events carrying `author_email`, proving it is not per-command), and\n  a batch/deferred-commit write yields the same envelope fields.\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py` (author_email helper + envelope stamping + cache)\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py` (present-only author_email/author_id surfacing)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783819999488240001,"uuid":"e5807487-b48c-4840-9e89-66b1f1c08ab6"}